New Order in the Middle East
President Bush, Palestinian Prime Minister Mazen, and Israeli Prime Minister Sharon want to meet.
Is America serious about reaching a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians?
How does this meeting fit into America's Middle East strategy?
Richard Haass, head of the planning staff at the U.S. State Department, explains his "roadmap" for the entire Middle East.
What was achieved in Iraq - and what, above all, the Iraqi people can now build with the help of Americans - will determine the future of one of the most important countries in the Middle East.
A transparent, market-oriented, and peaceful Iraq could promote reforms and growth throughout the region.
However, it will take some time until far-reaching changes in Iraq and throughout the entire Middle East come to fruition.
The challenge in Iraq after Saddam has humanitarian, security-policy, as well as economic and political aspects.
Thanks to the pre-planning of the Americans and the whole world, as well as the rapid, focused, and goal-directed intervention of coalition troops during the war, the humanitarian challenge is less than initially assumed.
Here and there there is a need for humanitarian aid, but fortunately the announced massive crisis never materialized.
There are relatively few refugees and internally displaced persons within Iraq. Supplies of food, water, and medicines are generally sufficient or improving.
The American government has provided approximately 600 million dollars through the UN and non-governmental organizations for immediate humanitarian assistance.
We also need to restore the basic order in Iraq.
Security is the indispensable prerequisite for a sustainable improvement of the situation after the war. Without security, people cannot rebuild their country, return to work, or go back to school.
Nach dem Sturz Saddams kam es zu einer Welle von Plünderungen, Gesetzlosigkeit und Abrechnungen.
Nun ist es oberste Priorität, dieser Gewalt ein Ende zu setzen.
Darüber hinaus muss es die Aufgabe internationaler Truppen sein, alle Massenvernichtungswaffen sicherzustellen und zu eliminieren, den gewaltvollen Ausbruch ethnischer und religiöser Konflikte zu verhindern und sicherzustellen, dass keiner der Nachbarn des Irak die ohnehin schon labile Situation noch verschlimmert.
Langfristig müssen wir den Irakern helfen, ihre Polizei- und Militärstrukturen wiederaufzubauen, so dass sie für ihre eigene Sicherheit sorgen können, ohne dabei jemanden zu bedrohen.
Der wirtschaftliche Wiederaufbau sollte genauer als wirtschaftliche Erneuerung betrachtet werden.
<s>The physical capital is in better condition than expected and the modern Iraq has a large reservoir of human capital.
<s>In contrast to many other post-war scenarios, there is a lot to process in Iraq in terms of resources.
<s>The USA is providing more than two billion dollars to support the first reconstruction efforts.
<s>The oil production is being raised to a better level.
<s>Among the longer-term challenges are the increase in oil production and the reduction of the enormous debts of Iraq.
The decision of the UN Security Council to lift all sanctions is very welcome.
Given the many religious, ethnic, geographic, and political divides in Iraqi society, helping to politically renew Iraq is likely the most challenging task.
The cynics and skeptics are wrong here.
The aim of the Americans – a cohesive Iraq where the rule of law is respected and a democratic government comes to power – is no pipe dream, especially not because Iraq has a educated population and a reasonably large middle class.
The international community can achieve this goal if it is willing to stick with the course and cooperate with the Iraqis until the principles of a democratic society are realized.
Responsible Iraqi leaders must be supported so that the enormous political potential for constructive decisions can be utilized.
The developments in Iraq will certainly have effects on the entire region, but they will not determine the fate of the Middle East.
There is scarcely an issue in foreign policy that more strongly occupies and polarizes public opinion than the Palestinian question.
About a year ago, President George W. Bush declared his goal of a democratic Palestinian state living in peace with Israel.
In cooperation with Russia, the EU, and the United Nations, the USA developed a roadmap that brings us step-by-step closer to this goal.
A new Palestinian government and the new prime minister represent an important step in this direction.
Now, Palestinians and Israelis must be brought to set this process in motion and take measures to improve the situation before more far-reaching issues can be addressed at the negotiating table.
Finally, it cannot be allowed that terrorists render the peace process ineffective for all time.
But a solution to the Palestinian question is not automatically a solution to all problems in the Middle East.
The challenges posed to us by Iran are clear and unambiguous. This country develops weapons of mass destruction and supported terrorism.
<s>Such behavior violates the norms and rules of the international community and isolates Iran and its people.
<s>If Iran continues in this manner, it will have consequences.
<s>However, if the focus shifts away from terror and the construction of catastrophic weapons, the US is willing to resume good relations with this country.
<s>Just as the US is willing to engage with Syria if significant attitudinal changes occur there.
<s>A more general issue is the relative lack of openness in the political and economic systems in the region.
Tolerated by the United States for too long was the "democratic exception" in the Muslim Middle East.
As long as governments were friendly and supported regional stability, there was no reason for outsiders to advocate for representative forms of government.
We painfully felt that closed political systems lead to resentments and extremism against the interests of the United States, the West, and the entire world.
This is why we support democracy and political reforms through the Partnership Initiative for the Middle East, which was launched by Secretary of State Colin Powell in December 2002.
Even closed economic systems pose a danger.
<s>As the previous "Arab Human Development Report" (Report on the Development Status of Arab Countries) shows, the Arab countries of the Middle East lag far behind other regions in terms of personal freedom, women's rights, as well as economic and social development.
<s>These countries had to watch economic boom pass them by for too long.
<s>President Bush is determined to share the benefits of economic freedom with the Arabs.
<s>If his recently expressed proposal for a free trade zone between the USA and the Middle East within a decade were to be realized, that would provide a solid foundation for such development.
